<DOC><DOCNO> AP890307-0186 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 2217EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Mongolia     03-07 0159</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Soviet-Mongolia,0164</SECOND><HEAD>Soviets Begin Troop Withdrawal from Mongolia</HEAD><DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Soviet Union has begun withdrawingthree-quarters of its troops from Mongolia as promised, includingthe entire Soviet air force there, Foreign Ministry spokesmanGennady I. Gerasimov announced Tuesday.   He did not tell reporters when the pullout would be completed orhow many troops were involved.   Mongolia lies between China and the Soviet Union. Beijing saysremoval of Soviet troops from the region is a necessary step toimproving relations between the two communist giants. PresidentMikhail S. Gorbachev is to travel to Beijing on May 15 for the firstChinese-Soviet summit in 30 years.   Gorbachev announced the withdrawals from Mongolia on Jan. 18.   Moscow began withdrawing its troops from Mongolia in 1987, butdid not say how many were there. Western analysts estimated the sizeof the Soviet force at 40,000 to 60,000 troops before withdrawals.   The Soviet Union also is withdrawing troops from Eastern Europe.</TEXT></DOC>